fears"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Salesforce CEO Marc Benioff's biggest AI fears</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">The late Stephen Hawking warned against an AI-centered future for humanity, and with movies like Terminator and The Minority Report, we can understand that caution. That said, other movies like WALL-E and Big Hero 6 present much more optimistic scenarios that we might see. Yahoo Finance Executive Editor Brian Sozzi sat down with Salesforce (CRM) CEO Marc Benioff at Dreamforce 2024, who made the point that, "technology is not good or bad, it's what you do with it. It's our job to guide the technology and set the values." Salesforce has exemplified that be building The Einstein Trust Layer as an active step toward AI safety, security, and responsibility. strike: What to watch next week"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">September jobs report, port strike: What to watch next week</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Market Domination Hosts Julie Hyman and Josh Lipton break down what to watch next week. Tesla (TSLA) is expected to report its third quarter delivery numbers on Wednesday. Analysts expect deliveries to come in at about 462,000, with some projecting it to be as high as 470,000. Monthly JOLTS (Job Openings and Labor Turnover Survey) data will be released on Tuesday. Economists anticipate openings will increase to 7.7 million in August. On Friday, investors will get the September jobs report, where they expect 130,000 nonfarm payroll jobs to be added and the unemployment rate to hold steady at 4.2%. Nike (NKE), ConAgra (CAG), Cal-Maine Foods (CALM), Carnival (CCL), Levi's (LEVI), and Constellation Brands (STZ) are all expected to report their earnings next week. Finally, Tuesday could mark the start of the first port strike along the Gulf and East Coast in nearly 50 years. For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Market Domination Overtime. data-testid="storyitem" role="article"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small thumb     yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:img;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:Apple%20still%20AI%20winner%20despite%20iPhone%2016%20reception%3A%20Analyst;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:5;g:ec73742b-3c65-373b-8957-1af791704b21" 16 reception: Analyst"><div style="display: contents; --border-radius:var(--border-radius-m); --aspect-ratio:4/3;"> <img class="tw-bg-opacity-25  yf-13q9uv1" alt="Apple still AI winner despite iPhone 16 reception: Analyst" src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/sIEXCz6P4n5LkaHVgmG9Rg--~B/Zmk9c3RyaW07aD0xMjY7cT04MDt3PTE2ODthcHBpZD15dGFjaHlvbg--/https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2024-09/582253b0-7d13-11ef-bfff-fd41228acb0c.cf.webp" srcset="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/vokdJHP90vIQA1oCLrzFjw--~B/Zmk9c3RyaW07aD0yNTI7cT04MDt3PTMzNjthcHBpZD15dGFjaHlvbg--/https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2024-09/582253b0-7d13-11ef-bfff-fd41228acb0c.cf.webp 2x" fetchpriority="auto" loading="lazy"></div>    </a> <div class="content yf-1sxfjua"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small titles noUnderline   yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:hdln;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:Apple%20still%20AI%20winner%20despite%20iPhone%2016%20reception%3A%20Analyst;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:5;g:ec73742b-3c65-373b-8957-1af791704b21" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/apple-still-ai-winner-despite-210713797.html" aria-label="Apple still AI winner despite iPhone 16 reception: Analyst" title="Apple still AI winner despite iPhone 16 reception: Analyst"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Apple still AI winner despite iPhone 16 reception: Analyst</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Apple's (AAPL) new iPhone 16 has received mixed reception. Antoine Chkaiban, New Street Research technology infrastructure analyst tells Julie Hyman and Josh Lipton on Market Domination to break down why he’s concerned about the iPhone maker in the near term despite expecting the company to be a major benefactor of artificial intelligence (AI). “We're concerned about the upcoming cycle for a number of reasons,” Chkaiban says. “There are early data points suggesting that iPhone 16 reception is poor. Users are often disappointed. They see limited innovation. He adds that Apple Intelligence being delayed until after the initial launch of the device “doesn't really help.” Among the other factors contributing to Apple’s near-term headwinds are shortening refresh cycles as “iPhone users hold onto their devices for longer” and increased competition in China. Another concern is a general weakness in consumer demand. Chkaiban projects Apple will ship 215 million iPhones in fiscal 2025, which is 10% below consensus estimates. Despite near-term concerns, the analyst says Apple is in a prime position in the AI era. He explains, “The generative AI iPhone revolution indeed won't be hardware-driven. It will happen over multiple cycles. It won't create a near-term product cycle, but it will still revolutionize the user experience over time and I do believe that Apple is very well positioned to capture some value as they control a large ecosystem of high-end devices.” “Over coming years, I think Apple can do well with generative AI, with Apple intelligence getting rolled out. But it's not going to drive a near-term product cycle. That's what we're concerned about.” He expects that Apple’s revenue will grow, but this growth will be driven by services rather than device sales. “Bottom line is Apple can probably grow revenues mid to high single digits and earnings between low-to-mid teens. And so yes, over the long run, I think Apple is definitely a good name to own. And if there is indeed a pullback related to weakness in the current cycle, that would probably create a good entry point.” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Market Domination. This post was written by Naomi Buchanan.</p>  </a> <div class="footer yf-1sxfjua">   <div class="publishing yf-1weyqlp">Yahoo Finance Video <i aria-hidden="true" data-svelte-h="svelte-sg6bkb">•</i> 15 hours ago</div> <div class="taxonomy-links yf-13tszyc"><a data-testid="ticker-container" class="ticker x-small    hover2   border  streaming   yf-1jpysdn" aria-label="AAPL" data-ylk="elm:qte;elmt:link;itc:0;sec:sector-news;slk:AAPL;subsec:all;cpos:5" href="/quote/AAPL/" title="AAPL"> <div class="name yf-1jpysdn"> <span class="symbol yf-1jpysdn">AAPL</span> </div> <fin-streamer class="percentChange yf-1jpysdn" data-symbol="AAPL" data-field="regularMarketChangePercent" data-trend="txt" data-pricehint="2" data-tstyle="default" active><span class="txt-positive yf-1jpysdn">+0.12%</span></fin-streamer> </a> </div></div></div> </section>  </li>      <li class="stream-item  yf-ovk92u"> <section class="container sz-x-large stream  yf-1sxfjua responsive" data-testid="storyitem" role="article"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small thumb     yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:img;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:Novo%20Nordisk%20stock%20closes%20lower%2C%20analyst%20warns%20about%20Wegovy%20sales;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:6;g:75c2efda-ea16-370c-ad9e-11c8880b71b8" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/novo-nordisk-stock-closes-lower-205039022.html" aria-label="Novo Nordisk stock closes lower, analyst warns about Wegovy sales" title="Novo Nordisk stock closes lower, analyst warns about Wegovy sales"><div style="display: contents; data-ylk="elm:hdln;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:Adjusting%20your%20portfolio%20to%20weather%20election%20volatility;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:10;g:2d2e0407-5e99-387f-b6fa-af3acd8aceda" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/adjusting-portfolio-weather-election-volatility-163240315.html" aria-label="Adjusting your portfolio to weather election volatility" title="Adjusting your portfolio to weather election volatility"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Adjusting your portfolio to weather election volatility</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Matt Powers, Powers Advisory Group managing partner, joins Alexandra Canal on Wealth! to discuss how to best position your portfolio in a rate easing cycle, considering it's an election year. In the lower interest rate environment, Powers focuses on traditional defensive sectors like utilities, consumer staples, and financials, noting that “we still expect some short-term volatility as we enter October, which is historically the most volatile month of the year in election years.” He names Target as a good option to weather the expected volatility. "We're a dividend growth firm that's kind of our core focus, but they've got a great history of growing their dividend. But beyond that their recent earnings report, they beat on both earnings per share and revenue. And they've returned to a growth mode after a long stretch of underperformance, improved digital sales last quarter, 8%, was up in in-store sales as well. So we just think they're positioned nicely moving forward.” On the fixed-income side, Powers says, “We really say target the intermediate, the middle. And keep some short-term liquidity available… The theme really is to move away from the short term, extend your duration slightly before more rate cuts.” For investors considering adjusting their portfolio ahead of possible October volatility and the election, Powers says, “I don't think that any big knee-jerk changes before an election are a good idea because we don't know, obviously, who's going to win the election.” He adds, “We're looking at a reallocation really towards dividend-based side and dividend-based ETFs. So some broad-based exposure and capturing higher yields and likely some appreciation as funds flow into this area.” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Wealth! Defiance ETFs CEO &amp; CIO Sylvia Jablonski joins Catalysts to discuss why the stock remains attractive despite these allegations. Jablonski acknowledges the risk that the allegations could prove true but views the stock's recent drop as a buying opportunity. She emphasizes that if the allegations are invalid or can be addressed, Super Micro remains "critical to the future growth of AI infrastructure." Given the company's strong position in the AI market, Jablonski believes that once these allegations are resolved, "the stock goes back into its meteoric rise." "Yes, there is some risk in the short-term that there's some volatility and some additional pullback, but I don't think that this company is necessarily going away. What they do is critical to the AI infrastructure, valuations or not. I think it's a company that is going to continue to skyrocket just because of the product that they deliver. Now, given this regulatory overhang we need to see what the result is," she tells Yahoo Finance. data-ylk="elm:hdln;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:Nvidia%20stock%20gains%20depends%20on%20'overall%20macro'%20in%20markets;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:14;g:33bb0519-7e76-3841-aed9-f9bdd31979b5" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/nvidia-stock-gains-depends-overall-145248453.html" aria-label="Nvidia stock gains depends on 'overall macro' in markets" title="Nvidia stock gains depends on 'overall macro' in markets"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Nvidia stock gains depends on 'overall macro' in markets</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Shares of Nvidia (NVDA) are reversing some gains after closing higher for four consecutive days. Radio Free Mobile Founder Richard Windsor joins Morning Brief to discuss his outlook on the company following this run. Windsor emphasizes that Nvidia's continued growth "depends on the overall macro." For investors looking to enter the AI trade, he states that Nvidia is "the lowest risk way" to do so. However, he notes that investors must consider the broader market direction. Due to Nvidia stock's nature, Windsor explains that if markets sell off, Nvidia will fall significantly, adding, "Consequently, I think it's [Nvidia stock] going to go back and forth, I suspect in line or amplify the signal of the market rather than anything specific to Nvidia." With Nvidia's next earnings report not due until November, Windsor states, "Very, very big growth is expected in the stock. The year-over-year comparisons start to become more challenging, and so obviously you're gonna see the performance of the shares come back somewhat. And I think really that's all what's going on right here," he told Yahoo Finance. Despite near-term fluctuations, Windsor doesn't expect any other semiconductor stock to "get close to Nvidia in this generation" in terms of market share. Stock Created a Buying Opportunity?"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Has the Recent Dip in Adobe Stock Created a Buying Opportunity?</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Adobe (ADBE) stock plummeted after the company posted the earnings beat for FQ3 2024 on September 12. The stock is currently down 14% for the year, and this article is going to discuss whether the recent dip has created a buying opportunity. Adobe is known for its leading software products that help individuals and teams with graphic design, video editing, and web development, among many other use cases. It’s the product to go for if you’re a professional in the creativity and design businesses.</p>  </a> <div class="footer yf-1sxfjua">   <div class="publishing yf-1weyqlp">TipRanks <i This is the latest of a slew of tech companies who have been subject to regulatory overhang. RBC Capital Markets equity analyst Brad Erickson joins Catalysts to discuss why the regulatory challenges facing Big Tech companies should have little to no impact on investment strategies. Erickson explains that the Department of Justice is currently drafting a proposal for the judge in the default search case, outlining how they plan to \\\"remedy Google's ability to secure search status\\\" on smartphones. The DOJ has until December to submit this proposal, with the judge expected to rule by August 2025. However, Erickson notes that Google's planned appeal could extend the legal battle for several years. Due to this lengthy process, he believes Google's business \\\"isn't fundamentally about to change in sort of a seismic way,\\\" making the stock attractive at current levels. The train has so far left the station that unwinding the technology and the intricacy and the complexity of what these companies have built to ... drive their businesses, I don't know if it's totally possible to unpack that.\\\" For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Catalysts. Antoine Chkaiban, New Street Research technology infrastructure analyst tells\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:3;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://www.yahoo.com/author/julie-hyman/\\\"> Julie Hyman\u003C/a> and\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:4;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://www.yahoo.com/author/josh-lipton/\\\"> Josh Lipton\u003C/a> on Market Domination to break down why he’s concerned about the iPhone maker in the near term despite expecting the company to be a major benefactor of artificial intelligence (AI).\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>“We're concerned about the upcoming cycle for a number of reasons,” Chkaiban says. “There are early data points suggesting that iPhone 16 reception is poor. Users are often disappointed. They see limited innovation. He adds that Apple Intelligence being delayed until after the initial launch of the device “doesn't really help.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Among the other factors contributing to Apple’s near-term headwinds are shortening refresh cycles as “iPhone users hold onto their devices for longer” and increased competition in China. Another concern is a general weakness in consumer demand.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Chkaiban projects Apple will ship 215 million iPhones in fiscal 2025, which is 10% below consensus estimates.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Despite near-term concerns, the analyst says Apple is in a prime position in the AI era. He explains, “The generative AI iPhone revolution indeed won't be hardware-driven. It will happen over multiple cycles. It won't create a near-term product cycle, but it will still revolutionize the user experience over time and I do believe that Apple is very well positioned to capture some value as they control a large ecosystem of high-end devices.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>“Over coming years, I think Apple can do well with generative AI, with Apple intelligence getting rolled out. But it's not going to drive a near-term product cycle. That's what we're concerned about.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>He expects that Apple’s revenue will grow, but this growth will be driven by services rather than device sales. “Bottom line is Apple can probably grow revenues mid to high single digits and earnings between low-to-mid teens. And so yes, over the long run, I think Apple is definitely a good name to own. Antoine Chkaiban, New Street Research technology infrastructure analyst tells Julie Hyman and Josh Lipton on Market Domination to break down why he’s concerned about the iPhone maker in the near term despite expecting the company to be a major benefactor of artificial intelligence (AI). “We're concerned about the upcoming cycle for a number of reasons,” Chkaiban says. “There are early data points suggesting that iPhone 16 reception is poor. Users are often disappointed. They see limited innovation. He adds that Apple Intelligence being delayed until after the initial launch of the device “doesn't really help.” Among the other factors contributing to Apple’s near-term headwinds are shortening refresh cycles as “iPhone users hold onto their devices for longer” and increased competition in China. Another concern is a general weakness in consumer demand. Chkaiban projects Apple will ship 215 million iPhones in fiscal 2025, which is 10% below consensus estimates. Despite near-term concerns, the analyst says Apple is in a prime position in the AI era. He explains, “The generative AI iPhone revolution indeed won't be hardware-driven. It will happen over multiple cycles. It won't create a near-term product cycle, but it will still revolutionize the user experience over time and I do believe that Apple is very well positioned to capture some value as they control a large ecosystem of high-end devices.” “Over coming years, I think Apple can do well with generative AI, with Apple intelligence getting rolled out. But it's not going to drive a near-term product cycle. That's what we're concerned about.” He expects that Apple’s revenue will grow, but this growth will be driven by services rather than device sales. “Bottom line is Apple can probably grow revenues mid to high single digits and earnings between low-to-mid teens. And so yes, over the long run, I think Apple is definitely a good name to own. And if there is indeed a pullback related to weakness in the current cycle, that would probably create a good entry point.” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Market Domination. Core PCE, which excludes volatile food and energy costs, increased by 2.7% compared to the same period last year.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Tiffany Wilding, PIMCO managing director and economist, explains, \\\"Overall, today's data was sort of broadly in line with expectations… \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:7;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/video/election-uncertainty-could-explain-labor-140653051.html\\\">We've come on a string of pretty good inflation readings over the last several months\u003C/a> and that was coming after an acceleration in inflation in the first quarter. So I think Fed officials are pretty feeling pretty good about where inflation is sitting,” Wilding tells Yahoo Finance.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Blake Gwinn, RBC Capital Markets head of US rates strategy, breaks down what he expects from the Federal Reserve after the first rate cut. He tells Yahoo Finance, “There are some upside risks around inflation, and if you look at our forecast for where the Fed is going to cut to our terminal rate, it's much higher than markets are expecting. We're at 4% to 4.25%. Markets are pricing much lower than that. The Fed's dots are much lower than that.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Shares of Costco (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:8;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/COST\\\">COST\u003C/a>) are sliding after the retailer posted a mixed fourth-quarter earnings report. Revenue came in at $79.70 billion, falling slightly below the expected $79.96 billion. Meanwhile, US comparable sales, ex-gasoline and currency impacts, were better than analysts were expecting. Roth Capital Partners senior research analyst Bill Kirk believes that \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:9;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/video/costcos-mixed-earnings-report-means-143609179.html\\\">Costco's stock is \\\"priced nearly for perfection,\\\" \u003C/a>telling Yahoo Finance, \\\"It's universally loved, it's operating extremely well, and the valuation and where it trades reflects that.\\\" While the stock is under a bit of pressure following the earnings report, he explains, \\\"Any little pause in momentum, any little hiccup in margin is accentuated when you have a valuation that high.\\\"\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Shares of Nvidia (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:10;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/NVDA\\\">NVDA\u003C/a>) are reversing some gains after closing higher for four consecutive days. Radio Free Mobile Founder Richard Windsor emphasizes that \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:11;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/video/nvidia-stock-gains-depends-overall-145248453.html\\\">Nvidia's continued growth \\\"depends on the overall macro.\\\"\u003C/a> For investors looking to enter the AI trade, he states that Nvidia is \\\"the lowest risk way\\\" to do so. However, he notes that investors must consider the broader market direction. Due to Nvidia stock's nature, Windsor explains that if markets sell off, Nvidia will fall significantly, adding, \\\"Consequently, I think it's [Nvidia stock] going to go back and forth, I suspect in line or amplify the signal of the market rather than anything specific to Nvidia.\\\"\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>\u003Cem>This post was written by Melanie Riehl\u003C/em>\u003C/p>\",\"summary\":\"On today's episode of Morning Brief, Hosts Seana Smith and Madison Mills analyze the market open and discuss some of the biggest stories from the trading week. As Wall Street opens for the final trading day of the week, Yahoo Finance Markets & Data editor Jared Blikre analyzes the top market trends, including the S&P 500's (^GSPC) 42nd record high and the weakening of the US dollar against the Japanese yen. August's Personal Consumption Expenditures (PCE) data — the Federal Reserve's preferred measure of inflation — came in line with economist expectations. The headline PCE figure showed a modest month-over-month increase of 0.1%, while rising by 2.2% year-over-year. Core PCE, which excludes volatile food and energy costs, increased by 2.7% compared to the same period last year. Tiffany Wilding, PIMCO managing director and economist, explains, \\\"Overall, today's data was sort of broadly in line with expectations… We've come on a string of pretty good inflation readings over the last several months and that was coming after an acceleration in inflation in the first quarter. So I think Fed officials are pretty feeling pretty good about where inflation is sitting,” Wilding tells Yahoo Finance. Blake Gwinn, RBC Capital Markets head of US rates strategy, breaks down what he expects from the Federal Reserve after the first rate cut. He tells Yahoo Finance, “There are some upside risks around inflation, and if you look at our forecast for where the Fed is going to cut to our terminal rate, it's much higher than markets are expecting. We're at 4% to 4.25%. Markets are pricing much lower than that. The Fed's dots are much lower than that.” Shares of Costco (COST) are sliding after the retailer posted a mixed fourth-quarter earnings report. Revenue came in at $79.70 billion, falling slightly below the expected $79.96 billion. Meanwhile, US comparable sales, ex-gasoline and currency impacts, were better than analysts were expecting. Roth Capital Partners senior research analyst Bill Kirk believes that Costco's stock is \\\"priced nearly for perfection,\\\" telling Yahoo Finance, \\\"It's universally loved, it's operating extremely well, and the valuation and where it trades reflects that.\\\" While the stock is under a bit of pressure following the earnings report, he explains, \\\"Any little pause in momentum, any little hiccup in margin is accentuated when you have a valuation that high.\\\" Shares of Nvidia (NVDA) are reversing some gains after closing higher for four consecutive days. Radio Free Mobile Founder Richard Windsor emphasizes that Nvidia's continued growth \\\"depends on the overall macro.\\\" For investors looking to enter the AI trade, he states that Nvidia is \\\"the lowest risk way\\\" to do so. However, he notes that investors must consider the broader market direction. Due to Nvidia stock's nature, Windsor explains that if markets sell off, Nvidia will fall significantly, adding, \\\"Consequently, I think it's [Nvidia stock] going to go back and forth, I suspect in line or amplify the signal of the market rather than anything specific to Nvidia.\\\" This post was written by Melanie CEO Marc Benioff's biggest AI fears\",\"description\":\"\u003Cp>The late Stephen Hawking warned against an AI-centered future for humanity, and with movies like Terminator and The Minority Report, we can understand that caution. That said, other movies like WALL-E and Big Hero 6 present much more optimistic scenarios that we might see. Yahoo Finance Executive Editor \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:1;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://www.yahoo.com/author/brian-sozzi/\\\">Brian Sozzi\u003C/a> sat down with Salesforce (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:2;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/CRM\\\">CRM\u003C/a>) CEO Marc Benioff at Dreamforce 2024, who made the point that, \\\"technology is not good or bad, it's what you do with it. It's our job to guide the technology and set the values.\\\" Salesforce has exemplified that be building \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:3;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://www.salesforce.com/artificial-intelligence/trusted-ai/\\\">The Einstein Trust Layer\u003C/a> as an active step toward AI safety, security, and responsibility.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>For full episodes of Opening Bid, \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:4;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/videos/series/opening-bid/\\\">watch\u003C/a> on our website or \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:5;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://open.spotify.com/show/6blmkje6G8vLF8cVSWxa5A?si=13c787846e704eaa\\\">listen\u003C/a> on your favorite podcast platform.\u003C/p>\",\"summary\":\"The late Stephen Hawking warned against an AI-centered future for humanity, and with movies like Terminator and The Minority Report, we can understand that caution. That said, other movies like WALL-E and Big Hero 6 present much more optimistic scenarios that we might see. Yahoo Finance Executive Editor Brian Sozzi sat down with Salesforce (CRM) CEO Marc Benioff at Dreamforce 2024, who made the point that, \\\"technology is not good or bad, it's what you do with it. Antoine Chkaiban, New Street Research technology infrastructure analyst tells Julie Hyman and Josh Lipton on Market Domination to break down why he’s concerned about the iPhone maker in the near term despite expecting the company to be a major benefactor of artificial intelligence (AI). “We're concerned about the upcoming cycle for a number of reasons,” Chkaiban says. “There are early data points suggesting that iPhone 16 reception is poor. Users are often disappointed. They see limited innovation. He adds that Apple Intelligence being delayed until after the initial launch of the device “doesn't really help.” Among the other factors contributing to Apple’s near-term headwinds are shortening refresh cycles as “iPhone users hold onto their devices for longer” and increased competition in China. Another concern is a general weakness in consumer demand. Chkaiban projects Apple will ship 215 million iPhones in fiscal 2025, which is 10% below consensus estimates. Despite near-term concerns, the analyst says Apple is in a prime position in the AI era. He explains, “The generative AI iPhone revolution indeed won't be hardware-driven. It will happen over multiple cycles. It won't create a near-term product cycle, but it will still revolutionize the user experience over time and I do believe that Apple is very well positioned to capture some value as they control a large ecosystem of high-end devices.” “Over coming years, I think Apple can do well with generative AI, with Apple intelligence getting rolled out. But it's not going to drive a near-term product cycle. That's what we're concerned about.” He expects that Apple’s revenue will grow, but this growth will be driven by services rather than device sales. “Bottom line is Apple can probably grow revenues mid to high single digits and earnings between low-to-mid teens. And so yes, over the long run, I think Apple is definitely a good name to own. And if there is indeed a pullback related to weakness in the current cycle, that would probably create a good entry point.” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Market Domination. year.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>In the lower interest rate environment, Powers focuses on traditional defensive sectors like utilities, consumer staples, and financials, noting that “we still expect some short-term volatility as we enter October, which is historically the most volatile month of the year in election years.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>He names Target as a good option to weather the expected volatility. \\\"We're a dividend growth firm that's kind of our core focus, but they've got a great history of growing their dividend. But beyond that their recent earnings report, they beat on both earnings per share and revenue. And they've returned to a growth mode after a long stretch of underperformance, improved digital sales last quarter, 8%, was up in in-store sales as well. So we just think they're positioned nicely moving forward.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>On the fixed-income side, Powers says, “We really say target the intermediate, the middle. And keep some short-term liquidity available… The theme really is to move away from the short term, extend your duration slightly before more rate cuts.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>For investors considering adjusting their portfolio ahead of possible October volatility and the election, Powers says, “I don't think that any big knee-jerk changes before an election are a good idea because we don't know, obviously, who's going to win the election.” He adds, “We're looking at a reallocation really towards dividend-based side and dividend-based ETFs. So some broad-based exposure and capturing higher yields and likely some appreciation as funds flow into this area.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>For more expert insight and the latest market action, click \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:2;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/video/investors-eye-pce-costco-shares-113008963.html\\\">here\u003C/a> to watch this full episode of Wealth!\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>\u003Cem>This post was written by Naomi Buchanan.\u003C/em>\u003C/p>\",\"summary\":\"Matt Powers, Powers Advisory Group managing partner, joins Alexandra Canal on Wealth! to discuss how to best position your portfolio in a rate easing cycle, considering it's an election year. In the lower interest rate environment, Powers focuses on traditional defensive sectors like utilities, consumer staples, and financials, noting that “we still expect some short-term volatility as we enter October, which is historically the most volatile month of the year in election years.” He names Target as a good option to weather the expected volatility. \\\"We're a dividend growth firm that's kind of our core focus, but they've got a great history of growing their dividend. But beyond that their recent earnings report, they beat on both earnings per share and revenue. And they've returned to a growth mode after a long stretch of underperformance, improved digital sales last quarter, 8%, was up in in-store sales as well. So we just think they're positioned nicely moving forward.” On the fixed-income side, Powers says, “We really say target the intermediate, the middle. And keep some short-term liquidity available… The theme really is to move away from the short term, extend your duration slightly before more rate cuts.” For investors considering adjusting their portfolio ahead of possible October volatility and the election, Powers says, “I don't think that any big knee-jerk changes before an election are a good idea because we don't know, obviously, who's going to win the election.” He adds, “We're looking at a reallocation really towards dividend-based side and dividend-based ETFs. So some broad-based exposure and capturing higher yields and likely some appreciation as funds flow into this area.” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Wealth! Jablonski acknowledges the risk that the allegations could prove true but views the stock's recent drop as a buying opportunity. She emphasizes that if the allegations are invalid or can be addressed, Super Micro remains \\\"critical to the future growth of AI infrastructure.\\\" Given the company's strong position in the AI market, Jablonski believes that once these allegations are resolved, \\\"the stock goes back into its meteoric rise.\\\" \\\"Yes, there is some risk in the short-term that there's some volatility and some additional pullback, but I don't think that this company is necessarily going away. Windsor emphasizes that Nvidia's continued growth \\\"depends on the overall macro.\\\" For investors looking to enter the AI trade, he states that Nvidia is \\\"the lowest risk way\\\" to do so. However, he notes that investors must consider the broader market direction. Due to Nvidia stock's nature, Windsor explains that if markets sell off, Nvidia will fall significantly, adding, \\\"Consequently, I think it's [Nvidia stock] going to go back and forth, I suspect in line or amplify the signal of the market rather than anything specific to Nvidia.\\\" With Nvidia's next earnings report not due until November, Windsor states, \\\"Very, very big growth is expected in the stock. The year-over-year comparisons start to become more challenging, and so obviously you're gonna see the performance of the shares come back somewhat. And I think really that's all what's going on right here,\\\" he told Yahoo Finance. Despite near-term fluctuations, Windsor doesn't expect any other semiconductor stock to \\\"get close to Nvidia in this generation\\\" in terms of market share.
